UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Functions & Scope — The Heart of JavaScript\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nFunctions are the fundamental building blocks of JavaScript programs. Every piece of behavior — event handlers, API calls, transformations — lives in functions. Understanding functions deeply, including scope, closures, and the `this` keyword, is what separates beginners from intermediate JavaScript developers.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Write functions using all declaration styles\n- Understand function scope, block scope, and closure\n- Know when to use arrow functions vs regular functions\n- Use default parameters, rest parameters, and spread operator\n- Understand higher-order functions\n- Master the `this` keyword in different contexts\n\n---\n\n## 3. Function Declaration Styles\n\n```javascript\n// 1. Function Declaration (hoisted completely)\nfunction greet(name) {\n  return `Hello, ${name}!`;\n}\ngreet("Alice"); // ✅ Works before declaration (hoisted)\n\n// 2. Function Expression (NOT hoisted)\nconst greet = function(name) {\n  return `Hello, ${name}!`;\n};\n\n// 3. Arrow Function (no own this, no arguments object)\nconst greet = (name) => `Hello, ${name}!`;\nconst square = x => x * x;                     // Single param: no parens\nconst add = (a, b) => a + b;                   // Single expression: no braces\nconst multiply = (a, b) => {                   // Multi-line: braces + return\n  const result = a * b;\n  return result;\n};\nconst makeUser = (name) => ({ name, role: "user" }); // Return object literal: wrap in ()\n\n// 4. Named Function Expression\nconst factorial = function fact(n) {\n  return n <= 1 ? 1 : n * fact(n - 1); // Can call itself by name internally\n};\n\n// 5. Immediately Invoked Function Expression (IIFE)\n(function() {\n  const privateVar = "I am private";\n  // Code here has its own scope\n})();\n\n// Modern equivalent with block scope:\n{\n  const privateVar = "I am private";\n}\n```\n\n### Parameters: Defaults, Rest, Spread\n\n```javascript\n// Default parameters\nfunction createUser(name, role = "employee", department = "Engineering") {\n  return { name, role, department };\n}\ncreateUser("Alice");              // { name: "Alice", role: "employee", department: "Engineering" }\ncreateUser("Bob", "admin");       // { name: "Bob",  role: "admin", department: "Engineering" }\n\n// Rest parameters (...rest) — collect remaining arguments\nfunction sum(...numbers) {\n  return numbers.reduce((total, n) => total + n, 0);\n}\nsum(1, 2, 3, 4, 5); // 15\n\nfunction log(level, ...messages) {\n  console.log(`[${level}]`, ...messages);\n}\nlog("INFO", "User logged in", "ID: 123"); // [INFO] User logged in ID: 123\n\n// Spread operator (...) — expand array/iterable\nconst nums = [1, 2, 3];\nMath.max(...nums);       // 3 — equivalent to Math.max(1, 2, 3)\nconsole.log(...nums);    // 1 2 3\n\nconst arr1 = [1, 2];\nconst arr2 = [3, 4];\nconst combined = [...arr1, ...arr2, 5]; // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n```\n\n### Higher-Order Functions\n\n```javascript\n// Functions as arguments (callbacks)\nconst courses = [{ title: "HTML5", level: "Beginner" }, { title: "React", level: "Advanced" }];\ncourses.filter(c => c.level === "Beginner"); // [{ title: "HTML5", ... }]\ncourses.map(c => c.title.toUpperCase());      // ["HTML5", "REACT"]\ncourses.forEach(c => console.log(c.title));  // HTML5, React\n\n// Functions returning functions (factory pattern)\nfunction multiplier(factor) {\n  return (number) => number * factor;\n}\n\nconst double = multiplier(2);\nconst triple = multiplier(3);\n\ndouble(5); // 10\ntriple(4); // 12\n\n// Function composition\nconst pipe = (...fns) => (value) => fns.reduce((v, f) => f(v), value);\n\nconst processUser = pipe(\n  user => ({ ...user, email: user.email.toLowerCase() }),\n  user => ({ ...user, name: user.name.trim() }),\n  user => ({ ...user, xp: user.xp || 0 }),\n);\n\nprocessUser({ name: "  Alice  ", email: "ALICE@EXAMPLE.COM", xp: null });\n// { name: "Alice", email: "alice@example.com", xp: 0 }\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. The `this` Keyword\n\n```javascript\n// this depends on HOW the function is called\n\n// 1. Method call — this = the object\nconst user = {\n  name: "Alice",\n  greet() { return `Hello, I am ${this.name}`; },\n};\nuser.greet(); // "Hello, I am Alice"\n\n// 2. Standalone call — this = undefined (strict mode) or global\nfunction greet() { console.log(this); }\ngreet(); // undefined in strict mode\n\n// 3. Constructor (new) — this = new object\nfunction User(name) {\n  this.name = name;\n  this.role = "employee";\n}\nconst alice = new User("Alice");\n\n// 4. Arrow functions NEVER have their own this\n// They inherit this from enclosing scope\nconst timer = {\n  count: 0,\n  start() {\n    // WRONG: regular function loses ''this''\n    setInterval(function() {\n      this.count++; // this is undefined/global!\n    }, 1000);\n\n    // CORRECT: arrow inherits this from start()\n    setInterval(() => {\n      this.count++; // this = timer\n    }, 1000);\n  },\n};\n\n// 5. Explicit binding\nfunction greet() { return `Hello, ${this.name}`; }\n\ngreet.call({ name: "Alice" });         // Call with specific this\ngreet.apply({ name: "Bob" }, []);      // Apply with array args\nconst boundGreet = greet.bind({ name: "Charlie" }); // Create bound version\nboundGreet(); // "Hello, Charlie"\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Closures\n\n```javascript\n// A closure is when a function "remembers" variables from its outer scope\n// even after the outer function has returned\n\nfunction makeCounter(start = 0) {\n  let count = start;     // Private variable — only accessible via returned functions\n\n  return {\n    increment: () => ++count,\n    decrement: () => --count,\n    reset:     () => { count = start; },\n    getCount:  () => count,\n  };\n}\n\nconst counter = makeCounter(10);\ncounter.increment(); // 11\ncounter.increment(); // 12\ncounter.decrement(); // 11\ncounter.getCount();  // 11\ncounter.count;       // undefined — truly private!\n\n// Closure for memoization\nfunction memoize(fn) {\n  const cache = new Map();\n\n  return function(...args) {\n    const key = JSON.stringify(args);\n    if (cache.has(key)) {\n      console.log("Cache hit!");\n      return cache.get(key);\n    }\n    const result = fn.apply(this, args);\n    cache.set(key, result);\n    return result;\n  };\n}\n\nconst memoFib = memoize(function fib(n) {\n  if (n <= 1) return n;\n  return memoFib(n - 1) + memoFib(n - 2);\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is a closure and give a practical use case?**\n> A closure is a function that has access to variables from its outer (enclosing) scope even after that scope has finished executing. Practical use cases: private variables (module pattern), memoization, partial application/currying, event handlers that remember configuration, and counter factories.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between arrow functions and regular functions?**\n> Key differences: (1) Arrow functions don''t have their own `this` — they inherit from lexical scope. (2) Arrow functions cannot be used as constructors. (3) Arrow functions don''t have `arguments` object. (4) Arrow functions are always anonymous. Use arrow functions for callbacks and short expressions; use regular functions when you need `this` binding or `arguments`.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `call`, `apply`, and `bind`?**\n> All three set `this` explicitly. `call(thisArg, arg1, arg2)` — calls immediately with individual args. `apply(thisArg, [arg1, arg2])` — calls immediately with args as array. `bind(thisArg, arg1)` — returns a NEW function with `this` permanently bound, doesn''t call immediately. Use `bind` for event handlers and callbacks.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the difference between a function declaration and expression?\n2. What do arrow functions NOT have that regular functions do?\n3. What is a closure?\n4. What do rest parameters do?\n5. What is the difference between `call` and `bind`?\n6. What does a function return if there is no `return` statement?\n7. What is a higher-order function?\n8. What is an IIFE?\n9. In what context does `this` become the global object?\n10. What is function composition?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| Function declaration | Hoisted completely |\n| Arrow function | No own `this`, no `arguments` |\n| Default parameters | `function f(a, b = 10) {}` |\n| Rest parameters | `function f(...args) {}` — array |\n| Spread | `fn(...arr)` — expand iterable |\n| Closure | Function retains outer scope access |\n| `this` in arrow | Inherited from enclosing scope |\n| Higher-order | Function takes/returns function |\n\nFunctions are JavaScript''s primary abstraction mechanism. Master them — especially closures and the `this` keyword — and you unlock the ability to write elegant, modular, testable JavaScript.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l30301';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Arrays & Array Methods — Data Transformation Mastery\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nArrays are the most common data structure in JavaScript. More importantly, JavaScript''s built-in array methods (map, filter, reduce, find, etc.) let you transform data elegantly without loops. Every modern JavaScript codebase relies heavily on these methods — React state updates, API data processing, filtering lists.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Creating & Accessing Arrays\n\n```javascript\n// Creation\nconst fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"];\nconst nums   = new Array(5).fill(0);          // [0, 0, 0, 0, 0]\nconst matrix = Array.from({ length: 3 }, (_, i) => i + 1); // [1, 2, 3]\n\n// Access\nfruits[0];              // "apple"\nfruits[fruits.length - 1]; // "mango" (last)\nfruits.at(-1);          // "mango" (ES2022 — simpler)\nfruits.at(-2);          // "banana"\n\n// Destructuring\nconst [first, second, ...rest] = fruits;\n// first = "apple", second = "banana", rest = ["mango"]\n\nconst [a, , c] = fruits;  // Skip second: a = "apple", c = "mango"\n```\n\n## 3. Essential Array Methods\n\n```javascript\nconst courses = [\n  { id: 1, title: "HTML5",      level: "Beginner",     enrolled: 245, completed: false },\n  { id: 2, title: "CSS3",       level: "Beginner",     enrolled: 198, completed: true  },\n  { id: 3, title: "JavaScript", level: "Intermediate", enrolled: 312, completed: false },\n  { id: 4, title: "React",      level: "Advanced",     enrolled: 187, completed: true  },\n  { id: 5, title: "Node.js",    level: "Intermediate", enrolled: 156, completed: false },\n];\n\n// ── TRANSFORMATION ──────────────────────────────────────\n\n// map() — transform each element, returns NEW array\nconst titles = courses.map(c => c.title);\n// ["HTML5", "CSS3", "JavaScript", "React", "Node.js"]\n\nconst summaries = courses.map(c => ({\n  id:    c.id,\n  label: `${c.title} (${c.level})`,\n}));\n\n// ── FILTERING ───────────────────────────────────────────\n\n// filter() — keep matching elements, returns NEW array\nconst beginnerCourses = courses.filter(c => c.level === "Beginner");\nconst completedCourses = courses.filter(c => c.completed);\nconst popularCourses  = courses.filter(c => c.enrolled > 200);\n\n// Chaining filter + map\nconst completedTitles = courses\n  .filter(c => c.completed)\n  .map(c => c.title);\n// ["CSS3", "React"]\n\n// ── FINDING ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n// find() — first match or undefined\nconst htmlCourse = courses.find(c => c.id === 1);\n\n// findIndex() — index of first match or -1\nconst reactIndex = courses.findIndex(c => c.title === "React"); // 3\n\n// some() — true if AT LEAST ONE matches\nconst hasAdvanced = courses.some(c => c.level === "Advanced"); // true\n\n// every() — true if ALL match\nconst allCompleted = courses.every(c => c.completed); // false\n\n// includes() — contains exact value (primitives)\n[1, 2, 3].includes(2); // true\n\n// ── REDUCTION ───────────────────────────────────────────\n\n// reduce() — combine all elements into single value\nconst totalEnrolled = courses.reduce((sum, c) => sum + c.enrolled, 0); // 1098\n\nconst byLevel = courses.reduce((acc, c) => {\n  if (!acc[c.level]) acc[c.level] = [];\n  acc[c.level].push(c.title);\n  return acc;\n}, {});\n// { Beginner: [\"HTML5\", \"CSS3\"], Intermediate: [\"JavaScript\", \"Node.js\"], Advanced: [\"React\"] }\n\n// ── SORTING ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n// sort() — MUTATES original array! Always spread first\nconst sorted = [...courses].sort((a, b) => b.enrolled - a.enrolled);\n// Sorted by enrolled descending\n\nconst alphabetical = [...courses].sort((a, b) => a.title.localeCompare(b.title));\n\n// ── MUTATION METHODS ────────────────────────────────────\n\n// push() / pop() — add/remove from END\nconst arr = [1, 2, 3];\narr.push(4);       // [1, 2, 3, 4] — returns new length\narr.pop();         // [1, 2, 3]    — returns removed element\n\n// unshift() / shift() — add/remove from BEGINNING\narr.unshift(0);    // [0, 1, 2, 3]\narr.shift();       // [1, 2, 3]\n\n// splice() — insert/remove at position (MUTATES)\narr.splice(1, 0, 99);    // Insert 99 at index 1: [1, 99, 2, 3]\narr.splice(1, 1);        // Remove 1 at index 1: [1, 2, 3]\narr.splice(1, 2, 7, 8);  // Replace 2 items: [1, 7, 8]\n\n// ── IMMUTABLE ALTERNATIVES (prefer in React) ────────────\n\n// Add item\nconst newItems = [...items, newItem];\n\n// Remove item by index\nconst without = items.filter((_, i) => i !== targetIndex);\n\n// Update item\nconst updated = items.map((item, i) => i === targetIndex ? { ...item, done: true } : item);\n\n// ── FLAT & FLATMAP ──────────────────────────────────────\n\nconst nested = [[1, 2], [3, 4], [5]];\nnested.flat();        // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] — one level\nnested.flat(2);       // Deep flatten (2 levels)\n\nconst sentences = ["hello world", "foo bar"];\nconst words = sentences.flatMap(s => s.split(" "));\n// ["hello", "world", "foo", "bar"] — map then flatten\n\n// ── UTILITY ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n[1, 2, 3].join(" | ");      // "1 | 2 | 3"\n[1, 2, 3].reverse();        // [3, 2, 1] — MUTATES\n[1, 2, 3].slice(1, 3);      // [2, 3] — no mutation, exclusive end\nArray.isArray([1, 2]);       // true\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `map` and `forEach`?**\n> `map` transforms each element and returns a NEW array — it is a pure function with no side effects. `forEach` iterates and returns `undefined` — use it for side effects (logging, DOM updates). In functional programming, prefer `map` for transformations.\n\n**Q: How does `reduce` work? When would you use it?**\n> `reduce(callback, initialValue)` iterates the array, passing an accumulator and each element to the callback. The callback returns the updated accumulator. Use `reduce` when you need to transform an array into a single value: sum, object grouping, flattening, counting occurrences.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `find` and `filter`?**\n> `find` returns the FIRST matching element (or undefined). `filter` returns ALL matching elements as a new array. Use `find` when you need one specific item (by ID); use `filter` when you need all matching items.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Array Statistics\n```javascript\n// Given an array of numbers, write functions for:\nconst nums = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6, 5, 3, 5];\n// sum(), average(), min(), max(), unique()\n// Without using Math.min/max — use reduce\n```\n\n### Medium — Data Pipeline\n```javascript\n// Given users with courses, transform to:\n// { department: [{ name, completedCount }] }\n// sorted by completedCount descending within each department\n```\n\n### Hard — Implement reduce\n```javascript\n// Implement Array.prototype.myReduce from scratch\nArray.prototype.myReduce = function(callback, initialValue) {\n  // Your implementation\n};\n[1, 2, 3, 4].myReduce((sum, n) => sum + n, 0); // 10\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `map` return?\n2. What is the difference between `find` and `filter`?\n3. What does `reduce` ''s second argument (initial value) do?\n4. Which array methods mutate the original?\n5. How do you safely sort without mutating?\n6. What does `some()` return?\n7. What does `flat()` do?\n8. How do you remove duplicates from an array?\n9. What does `Array.from()` do?\n10. What is the difference between `slice` and `splice`?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Method | Returns | Mutates |\n|--------|---------|--------|\n| `map` | New array (transformed) | No |\n| `filter` | New array (subset) | No |\n| `reduce` | Single value | No |\n| `find` | Element or undefined | No |\n| `some/every` | Boolean | No |\n| `sort` | Sorted array | YES — spread first |\n| `push/pop` | Length/element | YES |\n| `slice` | New sub-array | No |\n| `splice` | Removed elements | YES |\n\nArray methods are the workhorses of data transformation in JavaScript. Prefer `map`, `filter`, `reduce` over loops — they are more expressive, composable, and easier to reason about.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l30401';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Objects & Destructuring — Working with Structured Data\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nObjects are JavaScript''s primary data structure for organizing related data. From API responses to component state to configuration objects — everything in JavaScript is or contains objects. Mastering objects, destructuring, and the spread/rest patterns is essential for modern JavaScript development.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Object Fundamentals\n\n```javascript\n// Object creation\nconst user = {\n  id:         1,\n  firstName:  "Alice",\n  lastName:   "Sharma",\n  department: "Engineering",\n  xp:         4850,\n  isAdmin:    false,\n  joinedAt:   new Date("2023-01-15"),\n  address:    { city: "Bengaluru", state: "KA" },\n  courses:    ["html5", "css3", "javascript"],\n  fullName() { return `${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`; },\n};\n\n// Property access\nuser.firstName;           // "Alice" (dot notation — prefer)\nuser["firstName"];        // "Alice" (bracket notation — for dynamic keys)\n\nconst key = "department";\nuser[key];                // "Engineering" (dynamic key)\n\n// Optional chaining — safe nested access\nuser?.address?.city;      // "Bengaluru"\nuser?.company?.name;      // undefined (not an error)\nuser?.courses?.[0];       // "html5"\nuser?.getProfile?.();     // Call method only if it exists\n\n// Nullish coalescing — default when null/undefined\nuser.xp ?? 0;             // 4850\nuser.bio ?? "No bio set"; // "No bio set"\nuser.xp || 0;             // 4850 (but 0 would fall through!)\n```\n\n## 3. Destructuring\n\n```javascript\n// Basic destructuring\nconst { firstName, lastName, department } = user;\n\n// Rename during destructuring\nconst { firstName: name, xp: points } = user;\n// name = "Alice", points = 4850\n\n// Default values\nconst { bio = "No bio", isAdmin = false } = user;\n\n// Nested destructuring\nconst { address: { city, state } } = user;\n// city = "Bengaluru", state = "KA"\n\n// Array in object\nconst { courses: [firstCourse, ...otherCourses] } = user;\n\n// Rest in destructuring\nconst { id, firstName: fName, ...rest } = user;\n// rest = { lastName, department, xp, ... } (everything except id, firstName)\n\n// Function parameter destructuring\nfunction displayUser({ firstName, lastName, department, xp = 0 }) {\n  return `${firstName} ${lastName} | ${department} | ${xp} XP`;\n}\ndisplayUser(user);\n\n// Rename in function params\nfunction greet({ firstName: name, department: dept }) {\n  return `Hello ${name} from ${dept}`;\n}\n\n// Swap variables\nlet a = 1, b = 2;\n[a, b] = [b, a];\n```\n\n## 4. Spread & Rest with Objects\n\n```javascript\n// Spread — copy/merge objects\nconst defaults = { theme: "light", language: "en", notifications: true };\nconst userPrefs = { theme: "dark", fontSize: 14 };\n\n// Merge (last one wins)\nconst merged = { ...defaults, ...userPrefs };\n// { theme: "dark", language: "en", notifications: true, fontSize: 14 }\n\n// Override specific property\nconst updated = { ...user, xp: user.xp + 100 };\n// New object with xp increased\n\n// Deep copy (one level only — shallow!)\nconst copy = { ...user };\ncopy.address.city = "Mumbai"; // MUTATES user.address too!\n\n// Deep copy for nested objects\nconst deepCopy = {\n  ...user,\n  address:  { ...user.address },\n  courses:  [...user.courses],\n};\n```\n\n## 5. Object Methods\n\n```javascript\n// Object.keys / values / entries\nconst config = { debug: true, version: "2.0", maxRetries: 3 };\n\nObject.keys(config);     // ["debug", "version", "maxRetries"]\nObject.values(config);   // [true, "2.0", 3]\nObject.entries(config);  // [["debug", true], ["version", "2.0"], ["maxRetries", 3]]\n\n// Iterate\nObject.entries(config).forEach(([key, value]) => {\n  console.log(`${key}: ${value}`);\n});\n\n// Object.fromEntries — convert entries back to object\nconst doubled = Object.fromEntries(\n  Object.entries(config).map(([k, v]) => [k, typeof v === "number" ? v * 2 : v])\n);\n\n// Object.assign — merge (mutates first arg)\nconst base = { a: 1, b: 2 };\nObject.assign(base, { b: 3, c: 4 }); // base = { a:1, b:3, c:4 }\n\n// Object.freeze — shallow immutability\nconst constants = Object.freeze({ MAX: 100, MIN: 0 });\nconstants.MAX = 200; // Silent fail (TypeError in strict mode)\n\n// Check property existence\n"firstName" in user;        // true\nuser.hasOwnProperty("xp"); // true\n```\n\n## 6. Computed Property Names & Shorthand\n\n```javascript\n// Property shorthand (when variable name = property name)\nconst name = "Alice";\nconst age  = 25;\nconst obj  = { name, age };  // { name: "Alice", age: 25 }\n\n// Computed property names\nconst field = "email";\nconst user  = { [field]: "alice@example.com" }; // { email: "alice@example.com" }\n\n// Dynamic key from variable\nfunction updateField(obj, field, value) {\n  return { ...obj, [field]: value };\n}\nupdateField(user, "xp", 5000); // { ...user, xp: 5000 }\n\n// Pattern in React forms\nfunction handleChange(e) {\n  const { name, value } = e.target;\n  setForm(prev => ({ ...prev, [name]: value }));\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between shallow copy and deep copy?**\n> Shallow copy (`{...obj}`, `Object.assign`) copies one level — nested objects/arrays are still shared references. Modifying a nested property affects both original and copy. Deep copy (`JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))`, `structuredClone()`) copies all levels — completely independent. Use shallow for simple objects, deep when nested mutability would cause bugs.\n\n**Q: What is optional chaining and when do you use it?**\n> Optional chaining (`?.`) short-circuits when the left side is null/undefined, returning undefined instead of throwing. Use it when accessing deeply nested properties from API responses or user data where intermediate values might be missing: `user?.profile?.avatar?.url ?? defaultAvatar`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `const { a: renamed } = obj` do?\n2. What does the spread operator do with objects?\n3. How do you merge two objects?\n4. What is optional chaining?\n5. What does `Object.entries()` return?\n6. What is the difference between `in` and `hasOwnProperty`?\n7. What is a shallow copy?\n8. How do you use a variable as an object key?\n9. What does nullish coalescing (`??`) do?\n10. How do you get all keys of an object?\n\n---\n\n## 9. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Syntax | Use Case |\n|---------|--------|----------|\n| Destructure | `const { a, b } = obj` | Extract properties |\n| Rename | `const { a: x } = obj` | Avoid naming conflicts |\n| Default | `const { a = 10 } = obj` | Provide fallback |\n| Spread | `{ ...obj1, ...obj2 }` | Copy/merge objects |\n| Rest | `const { a, ...rest } = obj` | Separate properties |\n| Optional chain | `obj?.a?.b` | Safe nested access |\n| Nullish | `a ?? b` | Default when null/undefined |\n| Computed key | `{ [variable]: value }` | Dynamic property names |\n\nObjects and destructuring are everywhere in modern JavaScript. Master these patterns and your code becomes cleaner, more expressive, and less error-prone.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l30501';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# DOM Manipulation — Controlling the Browser\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nThe DOM (Document Object Model) is the browser''s tree representation of your HTML. JavaScript can read and modify any part of the DOM — adding elements, changing text, updating styles, responding to events.\n\nDOM manipulation is what makes websites interactive. It is the bridge between your JavaScript logic and the visible page. Before React and other frameworks, pure DOM manipulation was THE way to build interactive UIs.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Selecting Elements\n\n```javascript\n// Modern selectors (CSS syntax)\ndocument.querySelector(".card");            // First match\ndocument.querySelectorAll(".card");         // All matches (NodeList)\ndocument.querySelector("#main-nav > a");    // CSS child combinator\ndocument.querySelector("[data-user-id]");   // Attribute selector\n\n// Legacy selectors (still useful)\ndocument.getElementById("header");          // Fastest — direct ID lookup\ndocument.getElementsByClassName("card");    // HTMLCollection (live)\ndocument.getElementsByTagName("input");     // HTMLCollection (live)\n\n// Traversal\nconst card = document.querySelector(".card");\ncard.parentElement;                 // Parent\ncard.parentNode;                    // Parent node (including text/comment)\ncard.children;                      // Direct element children\ncard.childNodes;                    // All child nodes including text\ncard.firstElementChild;             // First element child\ncard.lastElementChild;              // Last element child\ncard.nextElementSibling;            // Next sibling element\ncard.previousElementSibling;        // Previous sibling element\ncard.closest(".container");         // Nearest ancestor matching selector\n```\n\n## 3. Reading & Modifying Elements\n\n```javascript\nconst el = document.querySelector(".course-title");\n\n// Text content\nel.textContent;                  // Text only (no HTML)\nel.textContent = "New Title";    // Safe — escapes HTML entities\nel.innerHTML;                    // HTML string (DANGEROUS with user input)\nel.innerHTML = "<strong>Title</strong>"; // Parses HTML — XSS risk if user data!\nel.innerText;                    // Visible text (respects CSS display:none)\n\n// Attributes\nel.getAttribute("data-id");               // Get attribute\nel.setAttribute("data-id", "123");         // Set attribute\nel.removeAttribute("data-id");             // Remove attribute\nel.hasAttribute("disabled");               // Check\nel.dataset.userId;                          // data-user-id → dataset.userId\nel.dataset.userId = "456";                  // Set data attribute\n\n// Classes\nel.classList.add("active");               // Add class\nel.classList.remove("hidden");             // Remove class\nel.classList.toggle("open");               // Toggle\nel.classList.contains("error");            // Check\nel.classList.replace("old", "new");        // Replace\n\n// Inline styles\nel.style.color = "red";\nel.style.display = "none";\nel.style.cssText = "color: red; font-size: 16px;";\nel.style.setProperty("--custom-var", "#3b82f6"); // CSS variables\n\n// Computed styles (includes CSS file styles)\nconst styles = window.getComputedStyle(el);\nstyles.getPropertyValue("font-size"); // "16px"\n```\n\n## 4. Creating & Inserting Elements\n\n```javascript\n// Create element\nconst card = document.createElement("article");\ncard.className = "card";\ncard.innerHTML = `\n  <img src="${course.thumbnail}" alt="${course.title}">\n  <div class="card-body">\n    <h3 class="card-title">${escapeHtml(course.title)}</h3>\n    <p>${escapeHtml(course.description)}</p>\n    <button data-course-id="${course.id}">Enroll</button>\n  </div>\n`;\n\n// Security: escape user content before inserting as text\nfunction escapeHtml(str) {\n  const div = document.createElement("div");\n  div.textContent = str;\n  return div.innerHTML;\n}\n\n// Inserting elements\nconst container = document.querySelector(".course-grid");\n\ncontainer.appendChild(card);                    // Append at end\ncontainer.prepend(card);                        // Insert at beginning\ncontainer.insertBefore(card, referenceNode);    // Before specific node\ncontainer.after(card);                          // After the container itself\ncontainer.before(card);                         // Before the container itself\n\n// Modern insertAdjacentElement\ncontainer.insertAdjacentElement("beforeend", card);   // End of children\ncontainer.insertAdjacentElement("afterbegin", card);  // Start of children\ncontainer.insertAdjacentHTML("beforeend", "<div>...</div>"); // Insert HTML\n\n// Remove\ncard.remove();                          // Modern\ncard.parentNode.removeChild(card);      // Legacy\n\n// Replace\ncontainer.replaceChild(newCard, oldCard);\noldCard.replaceWith(newCard); // Modern\n```\n\n## 5. Efficient DOM Updates\n\n```javascript\n// DocumentFragment — batch inserts (one reflow instead of many)\nconst fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();\n\ncourses.forEach(course => {\n  const card = createCourseCard(course);\n  fragment.appendChild(card); // No DOM reflow yet\n});\n\ncontainer.appendChild(fragment); // Single DOM operation\n\n// Avoid reading and writing in same loop (forced reflow)\n// WRONG — triggers layout for every iteration\nconst elements = document.querySelectorAll(".card");\nelements.forEach(el => {\n  const height = el.offsetHeight;     // READ (forces layout)\n  el.style.height = height * 2 + "px"; // WRITE\n});\n\n// CORRECT — batch reads, then batch writes\nconst heights = [...elements].map(el => el.offsetHeight); // All reads\nelements.forEach((el, i) => {\n  el.style.height = heights[i] * 2 + "px"; // All writes\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `textContent` and `innerHTML`?**\n> `textContent` sets/gets pure text — HTML entities are escaped, so user-provided content is safe. `innerHTML` parses HTML strings — can create XSS vulnerabilities if you insert user-provided content directly. Always use `textContent` for text; use `innerHTML` only with trusted/escaped content.\n\n**Q: What is a DocumentFragment and why is it useful?**\n> A DocumentFragment is a lightweight DOM node that exists outside the live document tree. You can batch-append multiple elements to it without causing DOM reflows. When you finally append the fragment to the document, it inserts all children in one operation, causing just one reflow instead of N reflows.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the difference between `querySelector` and `getElementById`?\n2. What does `classList.toggle()` do?\n3. Why is `innerHTML = userInput` dangerous?\n4. What is a DocumentFragment?\n5. What is the difference between `textContent` and `innerText`?\n6. How do you add a class to an element?\n7. What does `closest()` do?\n8. What is the difference between `children` and `childNodes`?\n9. How do you insert HTML after an element''s last child?\n10. What is a forced reflow and how do you avoid it?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Operation | Method |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Select first | `querySelector(css)` |\n| Select all | `querySelectorAll(css)` |\n| Text content | `el.textContent = "..."` |\n| Add class | `el.classList.add("name")` |\n| Data attribute | `el.dataset.key` |\n| Create element | `document.createElement("tag")` |\n| Append | `parent.appendChild(el)` |\n| Remove | `el.remove()` |\n| Batch inserts | `DocumentFragment` |\n\nDOM manipulation is the foundation of browser JavaScript. Even if you use React or Vue in production, understanding the DOM makes you a better framework user and enables you to work outside frameworks when needed.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l30701';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Events & Event Handling — Responding to User Interactions\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nEvents are how users interact with web pages — clicks, keypresses, form submissions, mouse movements, scroll, window resize. Event handling is the mechanism that connects user actions to JavaScript code.\n\nProfessional event handling means understanding bubbling, delegation, custom events, and cleanup — not just slapping `onclick` on a button.\n\n---\n\n## 2. addEventListener — The Modern Way\n\n```javascript\n// Basic syntax\nelement.addEventListener(eventType, handler, options);\n\n// Simple example\nconst btn = document.querySelector("#enroll-btn");\n\nbtn.addEventListener("click", function(event) {\n  console.log("Clicked!");\n  console.log(event.target);     // Element that was clicked\n  console.log(event.currentTarget); // Element the listener is on\n});\n\n// Arrow function handler\nbtn.addEventListener("click", (e) => {\n  e.preventDefault();  // Prevent default browser behavior\n  handleEnroll();\n});\n\n// Remove a listener (must reference same function)\nfunction handleClick() { ... }\nbtn.addEventListener("click", handleClick);\nbtn.removeEventListener("click", handleClick); // Must be same reference!\n\n// Options\nbtn.addEventListener("click", handler, {\n  once:    true,   // Fires only once then auto-removes\n  capture: false,  // Listen during capture phase (default: bubble)\n  passive: true,   // Listener never calls preventDefault (scroll perf)\n});\n```\n\n## 3. Event Object\n\n```javascript\ndocument.addEventListener("click", (event) => {\n  event.target;            // Element that was clicked (most specific)\n  event.currentTarget;     // Element with the listener\n  event.type;              // "click"\n  event.timeStamp;         // When it occurred\n  event.bubbles;           // Does it bubble?\n  event.cancelable;        // Can preventDefault be called?\n\n  event.preventDefault();  // Stop default (link navigation, form submit)\n  event.stopPropagation(); // Stop bubbling\n  event.stopImmediatePropagation(); // Stop other listeners on same element too\n});\n\n// Mouse events\ndocument.addEventListener("mousemove", (e) => {\n  e.clientX; e.clientY;    // Relative to viewport\n  e.pageX;   e.pageY;      // Relative to document\n  e.offsetX; e.offsetY;    // Relative to target element\n  e.buttons;               // Which buttons are pressed\n});\n\n// Keyboard events\ndocument.addEventListener("keydown", (e) => {\n  e.key;        // "Enter", "Escape", "ArrowUp", "a", "A"\n  e.code;       // Physical key: "KeyA", "Enter", "Space"\n  e.ctrlKey;    // Was Ctrl held?\n  e.shiftKey;   // Was Shift held?\n  e.altKey;     // Was Alt held?\n  e.metaKey;    // Was Cmd/Win held?\n  e.repeat;     // Is key being held down?\n});\n```\n\n## 4. Event Bubbling & Delegation\n\n```javascript\n// BUBBLING: event fires on target, then bubbles up to ancestors\n// Target → Parent → Grandparent → ... → document → window\n\ndocument.querySelector(".list").addEventListener("click", (e) => {\n  console.log("list handler:", e.target, e.currentTarget);\n});\ndocument.querySelector(".item").addEventListener("click", (e) => {\n  console.log("item handler:", e.target);\n});\n\n// Click .item → logs BOTH: item first, then list\n\n// EVENT DELEGATION — one listener handles multiple children\n// Instead of adding listener to every button:\n\n// WRONG: N listeners for N buttons\ndocument.querySelectorAll(".delete-btn").forEach(btn => {\n  btn.addEventListener("click", handleDelete);\n});\n\n// CORRECT: one listener on the parent\ndocument.querySelector(".course-list").addEventListener("click", (e) => {\n  // Check what was clicked\n  const deleteBtn = e.target.closest("[data-action=''delete'']");\n  const enrollBtn = e.target.closest("[data-action=''enroll'']");\n\n  if (deleteBtn) {\n    const courseId = deleteBtn.dataset.courseId;\n    handleDelete(courseId);\n  }\n  if (enrollBtn) {\n    const courseId = enrollBtn.dataset.courseId;\n    handleEnroll(courseId);\n  }\n});\n\n// Now works for dynamically added buttons too!\n```\n\n## 5. Common Events Reference\n\n```javascript\n// Form events\nform.addEventListener("submit", (e) => {  e.preventDefault(); submitForm(e); });\ninput.addEventListener("input", (e) => {  updateUI(e.target.value); }); // Every keystroke\ninput.addEventListener("change", (e) => { validateField(e.target); }); // On blur/enter\ninput.addEventListener("focus", () => { highlightField(); });\ninput.addEventListener("blur",  () => { validateField(); });\n\n// Window events\nwindow.addEventListener("load",   () => { /* All resources loaded */ });\nwindow.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => { /* HTML parsed */ });\nwindow.addEventListener("resize", debounce(() => { updateLayout(); }, 200));\nwindow.addEventListener("scroll", throttle(() => { updateNav(); }, 100));\nwindow.addEventListener("beforeunload", (e) => {\n  if (hasUnsavedChanges) {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    e.returnValue = ""; // Triggers browser confirmation dialog\n  }\n});\n\n// Intersection Observer (better than scroll for visibility)\nconst observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {\n  entries.forEach(entry => {\n    if (entry.isIntersecting) {\n      entry.target.classList.add("visible");\n      observer.unobserve(entry.target); // Unobserve after animate-in\n    }\n  });\n}, { threshold: 0.1 });\n\ndocument.querySelectorAll(".animate-on-scroll").forEach(el => {\n  observer.observe(el);\n});\n```\n\n## 6. Custom Events\n\n```javascript\n// Dispatch custom events for component communication\nconst enrollEvent = new CustomEvent("course:enrolled", {\n  detail: { courseId: "html5", userId: 123 },\n  bubbles: true,\n});\nbtn.dispatchEvent(enrollEvent);\n\n// Listen for custom event\ndocument.addEventListener("course:enrolled", (e) => {\n  console.log("Enrolled:", e.detail.courseId);\n  updateProgressBar(e.detail.userId);\n});\n```\n\n## 7. Debounce & Throttle\n\n```javascript\n// Debounce: wait until user STOPS (search input, resize)\nfunction debounce(fn, delay) {\n  let timeout;\n  return function(...args) {\n    clearTimeout(timeout);\n    timeout = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);\n  };\n}\n\nconst searchInput = document.querySelector("#search");\nsearchInput.addEventListener("input", debounce((e) => {\n  fetchSearchResults(e.target.value);\n}, 300)); // Only fires 300ms after last keystroke\n\n// Throttle: limit to once per interval (scroll, mousemove)\nfunction throttle(fn, limit) {\n  let inThrottle;\n  return function(...args) {\n    if (!inThrottle) {\n      fn.apply(this, args);\n      inThrottle = true;\n      setTimeout(() => { inThrottle = false; }, limit);\n    }\n  };\n}\n\nwindow.addEventListener("scroll", throttle(() => {\n  updateScrollProgress();\n}, 100)); // Max once per 100ms\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is event delegation and why is it useful?**\n> Event delegation is attaching ONE event listener to a parent element instead of many listeners on individual children. It works because events bubble up. Benefits: (1) Better performance — fewer listeners. (2) Works for dynamically added elements — no need to re-attach listeners. (3) Less memory usage. Use `e.target.closest()` to identify which child was clicked.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `event.target` and `event.currentTarget`?**\n> `event.target` is the element that was actually clicked (the most specific element). `event.currentTarget` is the element that has the event listener attached. They differ when events bubble — if you click a `<span>` inside a `<button>`, `target` = span, `currentTarget` = button.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is event bubbling?\n2. What does `event.preventDefault()` do?\n3. What is event delegation and why use it?\n4. What is the difference between `target` and `currentTarget`?\n5. How do you remove an event listener?\n6. What does the `once` option do in `addEventListener`?\n7. What is a debounce?\n8. What events fire on form inputs?\n9. What is an IntersectionObserver used for?\n10. How do you create and dispatch a custom event?\n\n---\n\n## 10. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| `addEventListener` | Add event handlers programmatically |\n| `event.target` | What was clicked (specific) |\n| `event.currentTarget` | Where listener is attached |\n| `preventDefault()` | Stop browser default behavior |\n| `stopPropagation()` | Stop event from bubbling |\n| Event delegation | One listener on parent for all children |\n| Debounce | Delay until user stops (search) |\n| Throttle | Rate-limit frequency (scroll) |\n\nEvents are how JavaScript applications respond to the world. Master event handling — especially delegation, debouncing, and cleanup — and you can build responsive, efficient interfaces without performance issues.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l30801';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Error Handling — Writing Resilient JavaScript\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nErrors are inevitable in any real-world application — network failures, invalid user input, unexpected API responses, null references. The question is not whether errors will occur, but how gracefully your code handles them.\n\nPoor error handling creates apps that crash silently, show confusing error messages, or expose sensitive information. Good error handling creates resilient apps that degrade gracefully and help developers debug quickly.\n\n---\n\n## 2. try/catch/finally\n\n```javascript\n// Basic structure\ntry {\n  // Code that might throw\n  const data = JSON.parse(invalidJson);\n  processData(data);\n} catch (error) {\n  // Handle the error\n  console.error("JSON parse failed:", error.message);\n} finally {\n  // ALWAYS runs — cleanup\n  setLoading(false);\n}\n\n// Catching specific error types\ntry {\n  const response = await fetch("/api/data");\n  if (!response.ok) {\n    throw new Error(`HTTP error: ${response.status}`);\n  }\n  const data = await response.json();\n  return data;\n} catch (error) {\n  if (error instanceof TypeError) {\n    console.error("Network error:", error); // fetch failed (no internet)\n  } else if (error instanceof SyntaxError) {\n    console.error("Invalid JSON:", error);  // JSON.parse failed\n  } else {\n    console.error("Unknown error:", error);\n    throw error; // Re-throw if we can''t handle it\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Custom Error Classes\n\n```javascript\n// Custom error classes for better error handling\nclass AppError extends Error {\n  constructor(message, code, status = 500) {\n    super(message);\n    this.name = "AppError";\n    this.code  = code;\n    this.status = status;\n    this.timestamp = new Date().toISOString();\n  }\n}\n\nclass ValidationError extends AppError {\n  constructor(field, message) {\n    super(message, "VALIDATION_ERROR", 400);\n    this.name  = "ValidationError";\n    this.field = field;\n  }\n}\n\nclass NetworkError extends AppError {\n  constructor(url, status) {\n    super(`Request to ${url} failed with status ${status}`, "NETWORK_ERROR", status);\n    this.name = "NetworkError";\n    this.url  = url;\n  }\n}\n\nclass NotFoundError extends AppError {\n  constructor(resource, id) {\n    super(`${resource} with id ${id} not found`, "NOT_FOUND", 404);\n    this.name     = "NotFoundError";\n    this.resource = resource;\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage\ntry {\n  const user = await getUser(userId);\n  if (!user) throw new NotFoundError("User", userId);\n\n  if (!user.email.includes("@")) throw new ValidationError("email", "Invalid email");\n\n} catch (error) {\n  if (error instanceof NotFoundError) {\n    showNotFoundPage();\n  } else if (error instanceof ValidationError) {\n    showFieldError(error.field, error.message);\n  } else {\n    logToSentry(error);\n    showGenericError();\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Async Error Handling\n\n```javascript\n// async/await with try/catch\nasync function loadUserDashboard(userId) {\n  try {\n    const user    = await fetchUser(userId);\n    const courses = await fetchUserCourses(userId);\n    const badges  = await fetchUserBadges(userId);\n    return { user, courses, badges };\n  } catch (error) {\n    console.error("Dashboard load failed:", error);\n    throw error; // Re-throw for caller to handle UI\n  } finally {\n    setLoading(false);\n  }\n}\n\n// Promise chain error handling\nfetchUser(userId)\n  .then(user => fetchUserCourses(user.id))\n  .then(courses => displayCourses(courses))\n  .catch(error => {\n    if (error.status === 401) { redirectToLogin(); }\n    else if (error.status === 404) { showEmptyState(); }\n    else { showErrorMessage(error.message); }\n  })\n  .finally(() => setLoading(false));\n\n// Global unhandled rejection handler\nwindow.addEventListener("unhandledrejection", (event) => {\n  console.error("Unhandled Promise Rejection:", event.reason);\n  event.preventDefault(); // Prevent console error\n  logToMonitoring(event.reason);\n});\n\n// Helper: wrap async functions\nasync function safeAsync(fn, fallback) {\n  try {\n    return [await fn(), null];\n  } catch (error) {\n    return [fallback, error];\n  }\n}\n\nconst [user, error] = await safeAsync(() => fetchUser(id), null);\nif (error) { showError(error.message); return; }\n```\n\n## 5. Error Boundaries Pattern (Vanilla JS)\n\n```javascript\n// Error boundary wrapper\nfunction withErrorHandling(fn, errorHandler) {\n  return async function(...args) {\n    try {\n      return await fn(...args);\n    } catch (error) {\n      return errorHandler(error);\n    }\n  };\n}\n\nconst safeLoadCourses = withErrorHandling(\n  loadCourses,\n  (error) => {\n    showErrorToast(error.message);\n    return [];\n  }\n);\n\n// Validation utility\nfunction validate(data, rules) {\n  const errors = {};\n\n  Object.entries(rules).forEach(([field, validators]) => {\n    validators.forEach(({ check, message }) => {\n      if (!check(data[field])) {\n        if (!errors[field]) errors[field] = [];\n        errors[field].push(message);\n      }\n    });\n  });\n\n  if (Object.keys(errors).length > 0) {\n    const error = new ValidationError("multiple", "Validation failed");\n    error.errors = errors;\n    throw error;\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage\ntry {\n  validate(formData, {\n    email:    [{ check: v => v && v.includes("@"), message: "Valid email required" }],\n    password: [{ check: v => v && v.length >= 8,  message: "Min 8 characters" }],\n    name:     [{ check: v => v && v.trim().length > 0, message: "Name required" }],\n  });\n} catch (e) {\n  showFormErrors(e.errors);\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: When should you re-throw an error?**\n> Re-throw when your catch block cannot fully handle the error. If you catch a specific type but receive an unexpected type, re-throw. If you can log/enrich the error but the caller needs to make the UI decision, re-throw. Rule: catch only what you can handle; let others bubble up.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `Error.message` and `Error.stack`?**\n> `message` is the human-readable error description. `stack` is the full stack trace — a string showing the call chain from where the error was created. `stack` is invaluable for debugging but should never be shown to users. Log `stack` to your monitoring service (Sentry, LogRocket).\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `finally` do and when does it run?\n2. How do you create a custom error class?\n3. What is the difference between `throw` and `return` in a catch block?\n4. How do you handle errors in async/await?\n5. What is an unhandled promise rejection?\n6. When should you re-throw an error?\n7. What does `instanceof` do in error handling?\n8. What is an error boundary?\n9. What properties does the `Error` object have?\n10. How do you catch errors from `Promise.all()`?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| `try/catch/finally` | Handle and clean up after errors |\n| Custom errors | `class MyError extends Error {}` |\n| Re-throw | When you can''t handle it fully |\n| Async error | `try/catch` with await or `.catch()` |\n| `instanceof` | Check error type in catch |\n| Global handler | `unhandledrejection` event |\n| Error enrichment | Add context before re-throwing |\n\nError handling is a craft. Production-ready code anticipates failures, handles them gracefully, provides useful debug info to developers, and meaningful messages to users — never letting an unhandled exception crash the experience.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l31201';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# ES6+ Modules — Organizing JavaScript at Scale\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nBefore ES6 modules, JavaScript had no built-in module system. Large applications used global variables, IIFE patterns, or non-standard module systems (CommonJS, AMD). ES6 modules provide a standardized, clean way to split code into files with explicit imports and exports.\n\nEvery modern JavaScript application — React, Node.js, TypeScript — uses ES modules.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Export & Import\n\n```javascript\n// ====== file: utils/math.js ======\n\n// Named exports\nexport function add(a, b) { return a + b; }\nexport function multiply(a, b) { return a * b; }\nexport const PI = 3.14159;\nexport const MAX_RETRY = 3;\n\n// Export after declaration\nfunction subtract(a, b) { return a - b; }\nconst divide = (a, b) => a / b;\nexport { subtract, divide };\nexport { subtract as sub };   // Rename on export\n\n// Default export (one per file)\nexport default function formatNumber(n) {\n  return new Intl.NumberFormat("en-IN").format(n);\n}\n\n// ====== file: main.js ======\n\n// Named imports\nimport { add, multiply, PI } from "./utils/math.js";\n\n// Import with rename\nimport { add as sum, MAX_RETRY as RETRIES } from "./utils/math.js";\n\n// Default import (any name you choose)\nimport formatNum from "./utils/math.js";\n\n// Import everything as namespace\nimport * as math from "./utils/math.js";\nmath.add(1, 2);\nmath.PI;\nmath.default(12345); // Default export\n\n// Mixed: default + named\nimport formatNum, { add, PI } from "./utils/math.js";\n```\n\n## 3. Module Patterns\n\n```javascript\n// ====== Pattern 1: Feature Module ======\n// file: features/auth.js\n\nimport { supabase } from "../lib/supabase.js";\nimport { isAllowedEmail } from "../utils/validation.js";\n\nconst STATE = { user: null, loading: false };\n\nasync function signIn(email, password) {\n  if (!isAllowedEmail(email)) throw new Error("Domain not allowed");\n  STATE.loading = true;\n  try {\n    const { data, error } = await supabase.auth.signInWithPassword({ email, password });\n    if (error) throw error;\n    STATE.user = data.user;\n    return data.user;\n  } finally {\n    STATE.loading = false;\n  }\n}\n\nasync function signOut() {\n  await supabase.auth.signOut();\n  STATE.user = null;\n}\n\nfunction getCurrentUser() { return STATE.user; }\nfunction isLoading() { return STATE.loading; }\n\nexport { signIn, signOut, getCurrentUser, isLoading };\n\n// ====== Pattern 2: Re-export (barrel/index) ======\n// file: utils/index.js\nexport { formatDate, parseDate } from "./dates.js";\nexport { formatCurrency, parseCurrency } from "./currency.js";\nexport { capitalize, truncate } from "./strings.js";\nexport { debounce, throttle } from "./timing.js";\nexport * from "./validation.js";\n\n// Consumer can import everything from one place\nimport { formatDate, debounce, capitalize } from "../utils/index.js";\n\n// ====== Pattern 3: Constants module ======\n// file: constants.js\nexport const API_URL     = process.env.VITE_API_URL || "http://localhost:3000";\nexport const APP_VERSION = "2.1.0";\nexport const ROUTES = {\n  HOME:        "/",\n  COURSES:     "/courses",\n  DASHBOARD:   "/dashboard",\n  SIGN_IN:     "/auth/signin",\n};\nexport const HTTP_STATUS = {\n  OK:          200,\n  CREATED:     201,\n  BAD_REQUEST: 400,\n  UNAUTHORIZED: 401,\n  NOT_FOUND:   404,\n  SERVER_ERROR: 500,\n};\n```\n\n## 4. Dynamic Imports\n\n```javascript\n// Static import: always loads at startup\nimport { Chart } from "chart.js"; // Loaded even if user never views chart\n\n// Dynamic import: load on demand (code splitting)\nasync function showChart(data) {\n  // Only loads chart.js when this function is called\n  const { Chart } = await import("chart.js");\n  const chart = new Chart(canvas, { type: "bar", data });\n}\n\n// Lazy loading routes (React Router pattern)\nconst Dashboard = React.lazy(() => import("./pages/Dashboard"));\nconst Analytics = React.lazy(() => import("./pages/Analytics"));\n\n// Conditional loading based on features\nasync function initApp() {\n  if (user.isAdmin) {\n    const { AdminPanel } = await import("./components/AdminPanel.js");\n    AdminPanel.init();\n  }\n}\n\n// Bundle splitting with Vite/Webpack\n// Each dynamic import = separate chunk = separate network request\n// Reduces initial bundle size\n```\n\n## 5. CommonJS vs ES Modules\n\n```javascript\n// CommonJS (Node.js legacy, .cjs files)\nconst fs       = require("fs");               // Import\nconst { join } = require("path");             // Named\nmodule.exports = { add, multiply };           // Export\nmodule.exports.default = MyClass;             // Default-like\n\n// ES Modules (modern standard, .mjs or "type":"module" in package.json)\nimport fs       from "fs/promises";\nimport { join } from "path";\nexport { add, multiply };\nexport default MyClass;\n\n// Key differences:\n// CJS: synchronous, loads at runtime, can be conditional\n// ESM: asynchronous, static analysis possible (tree-shaking!), top-level only\n// ESM supports tree-shaking — bundlers can remove unused exports\n// CJS cannot be tree-shaken\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is tree-shaking and which module system supports it?**\n> Tree-shaking is when a bundler (Webpack, Rollup, Vite) removes unused exports from the final bundle. It only works with ES modules (`import`/`export`) because ESM is statically analyzable — the bundler can determine at build time which exports are used. CommonJS (`require`/`module.exports`) is dynamic and cannot be tree-shaken.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between named exports and default exports?**\n> Named exports: a file can have many, imported with `{ name }`, the name must match. Default export: a file has at most one, imported with any name you choose. Best practice: prefer named exports for better IDE autocomplete, refactoring, and tree-shaking. Use default export for components and classes.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. How do you export a function with a different name?\n2. What is a barrel file (index.js pattern)?\n3. What is the difference between `import * as` and destructured import?\n4. What is dynamic import and when do you use it?\n5. What is tree-shaking?\n6. How many default exports can a file have?\n7. What is the difference between CommonJS and ESM?\n8. How do you import a default and named export together?\n9. What is circular dependency and why is it a problem?\n10. What does `export { x as y }` do?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Syntax |\n|---------|--------|\n| Named export | `export function fn()` |\n| Default export | `export default function fn()` |\n| Named import | `import { fn } from "./mod.js"` |\n| Default import | `import fn from "./mod.js"` |\n| Re-export | `export { fn } from "./mod.js"` |\n| Namespace import | `import * as mod from "./mod.js"` |\n| Dynamic import | `const { fn } = await import("./mod.js")` |\n\nModules are the building blocks of large JavaScript applications. Good module design — clear separation of concerns, minimal dependencies, explicit exports — makes code maintainable, testable, and scalable.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l31301';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# OOP & Classes in JavaScript — Object-Oriented Patterns\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nJavaScript''s class syntax (ES6+) provides a clean way to write object-oriented code. Under the hood it is still prototype-based, but the class syntax is what you will see in every modern JavaScript codebase — especially when building UI components, services, and domain models.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Classes — Complete Syntax\n\n```javascript\nclass Course {\n  // Private fields (ES2022 — starts with #)\n  #id;\n  #enrolledUsers = new Set();\n\n  // Static field\n  static courseCount = 0;\n\n  // Constructor\n  constructor(id, title, level, maxEnrollment = 100) {\n    this.#id    = id;\n    this.title  = title;\n    this.level  = level;\n    this.maxEnrollment = maxEnrollment;\n    this.createdAt = new Date();\n    Course.courseCount++;\n  }\n\n  // Getter\n  get id() { return this.#id; }\n\n  get enrollmentCount() { return this.#enrolledUsers.size; }\n\n  get isFull() { return this.#enrolledUsers.size >= this.maxEnrollment; }\n\n  // Setter\n  set title(value) {\n    if (!value || value.trim().length === 0) throw new Error("Title cannot be empty");\n    this._title = value.trim();\n  }\n  get title() { return this._title; }\n\n  // Instance methods\n  enroll(userId) {\n    if (this.isFull) throw new Error(`Course "${this.title}" is full`);\n    this.#enrolledUsers.add(userId);\n    return this;\n  }\n\n  unenroll(userId) {\n    this.#enrolledUsers.delete(userId);\n    return this;\n  }\n\n  isEnrolled(userId) {\n    return this.#enrolledUsers.has(userId);\n  }\n\n  // Static methods\n  static fromJSON(json) {\n    const data = typeof json === "string" ? JSON.parse(json) : json;\n    return new Course(data.id, data.title, data.level, data.maxEnrollment);\n  }\n\n  static compareByTitle(a, b) {\n    return a.title.localeCompare(b.title);\n  }\n\n  // Serialization\n  toJSON() {\n    return {\n      id:              this.#id,\n      title:           this.title,\n      level:           this.level,\n      enrollmentCount: this.enrollmentCount,\n      maxEnrollment:   this.maxEnrollment,\n    };\n  }\n\n  toString() {\n    return `Course(${this.#id}): ${this.title} [${this.level}]`;\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage\nconst html = new Course("html5", "HTML5 Fundamentals", "Beginner");\nhtml.enroll("user-123").enroll("user-456"); // Method chaining\nhtml.enrollmentCount; // 2\nhtml.isFull;          // false\nhtml.id;              // "html5" (via getter)\nhtml.#id;             // SyntaxError — private!\nCourse.courseCount;   // 1\n```\n\n## 3. Inheritance\n\n```javascript\nclass User {\n  constructor(id, email, name) {\n    this.id    = id;\n    this.email = email;\n    this.name  = name;\n    this.xp    = 0;\n    this.joinedAt = new Date();\n  }\n\n  addXP(amount) {\n    this.xp += amount;\n    return this;\n  }\n\n  toString() {\n    return `User(${this.id}): ${this.name} [${this.xp} XP]`;\n  }\n}\n\nclass Employee extends User {\n  constructor(id, email, name, department, role = "employee") {\n    super(id, email, name);   // MUST call super() first\n    this.department = department;\n    this.role       = role;\n    this.courses    = [];\n  }\n\n  enroll(course) {\n    this.courses.push(course);\n    course.enroll(this.id);\n    return this;\n  }\n\n  getCompletedCourses() {\n    return this.courses.filter(c => c.completed);\n  }\n\n  // Override parent method\n  toString() {\n    return `${super.toString()} | ${this.department}`;\n  }\n}\n\nclass Admin extends Employee {\n  constructor(id, email, name) {\n    super(id, email, name, "Administration", "admin");\n    this.permissions = new Set(["manage_users", "manage_courses"]);\n  }\n\n  hasPermission(perm) { return this.permissions.has(perm); }\n\n  grantPermission(perm) {\n    this.permissions.add(perm);\n    return this;\n  }\n}\n\n// Polymorphism\nconst users = [\n  new User("u1", "viewer@co.com", "Viewer"),\n  new Employee("e1", "alice@co.com", "Alice", "Engineering"),\n  new Admin("a1", "admin@co.com", "Admin"),\n];\n\nusers.forEach(u => console.log(u.toString()));\n// Each calls the appropriate toString() for their class\n\n// instanceof\nnew Admin() instanceof Admin;    // true\nnew Admin() instanceof Employee; // true (inheritance chain)\nnew Admin() instanceof User;     // true\nnew Admin() instanceof Course;   // false\n```\n\n## 4. Mixins (Composition over Inheritance)\n\n```javascript\n// Problem: JavaScript has single inheritance\n// Solution: Mixins — add capabilities without inheritance\n\nconst Serializable = (Base) => class extends Base {\n  toJSON() { return JSON.stringify(this); }\n  static fromJSON(json) { return Object.assign(new this(), JSON.parse(json)); }\n};\n\nconst Timestamped = (Base) => class extends Base {\n  constructor(...args) {\n    super(...args);\n    this.createdAt = new Date();\n    this.updatedAt = new Date();\n  }\n  touch() { this.updatedAt = new Date(); }\n};\n\nconst Validatable = (Base) => class extends Base {\n  validate() {\n    const errors = this.validationRules?.() ?? {};\n    if (Object.keys(errors).length > 0) throw new ValidationError(errors);\n    return true;\n  }\n};\n\n// Compose\nclass Course extends Timestamped(Serializable(Validatable(class {}))) {\n  constructor(id, title) {\n    super();\n    this.id    = id;\n    this.title = title;\n  }\n  validationRules() {\n    const errors = {};\n    if (!this.title) errors.title = "Title is required";\n    return errors;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between a class and an object?**\n> A class is a blueprint/template — it defines structure and behavior. An object is an instance created FROM a class using `new`. Classes define what properties and methods instances will have; objects are the actual data in memory.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `static` and instance members?**\n> Instance members belong to each object created from the class — `this.name` is different for each instance. Static members belong to the CLASS itself — `Course.courseCount` is shared across all instances and accessed via the class name, not `this`.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between inheritance and composition? Which is better?**\n> Inheritance: "is-a" relationship — Admin extends Employee. Composition: "has-a" relationship — User has a permissions module. Composition is generally preferred (Mixins, dependency injection) because it''s more flexible, avoids deep inheritance chains, and makes testing easier. Inheritance creates tight coupling and the "fragile base class" problem.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `super()` do in a constructor?\n2. How do you make a property private in JavaScript?\n3. What is a static method and how do you call it?\n4. What is a getter and setter?\n5. What is the difference between `instanceof` and `typeof`?\n6. What is method overriding?\n7. What is a mixin?\n8. How does the prototype chain relate to class inheritance?\n9. What is the "composition over inheritance" principle?\n10. Can a class extend multiple classes?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Syntax |\n|---------|--------|\n| Class | `class Name { constructor() {} }` |\n| Private field | `#field` |\n| Static | `static method()` or `static field = value` |\n| Getter/setter | `get name() {}` / `set name(v) {}` |\n| Inheritance | `class Child extends Parent {}` |\n| Super | `super(args)` / `super.method()` |\n| Instanceof | `obj instanceof ClassName` |\n| Mixin | `class X extends Mixin(Base) {}` |\n\nClasses and OOP patterns enable organizing complex JavaScript code into maintainable, reusable components. Master class syntax, inheritance, and composition, and you have the tools to build large-scale applications.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l31401';
